<module status="bronze">
  <h>bho</h>
  <p><g>bho</g>
    <en>from</en> is the (leniting) ablative <a href="?xx=prepositions/prepositions"
    >preposition</a>.</p>

  <section>
    <h>forms</h>
    <section id="indefinite">
      <h>indefinite</h>
      <p>The default form of the ablative preposition is simply <g>bho</g> – <ul>
          <li><m>bho</m> thaigh <en>from a house</en></li>
          <li><m>bho</m> aislingean <en>from dreams</en></li>
          <li><m>bho</m> Nirribhidh <en>from Norway</en></li>
          <li><m>bho</m> thrì làithean <en>from three days</en></li>
        </ul></p>
      <p>Note that all forms of the ablative preposition can be spelled without the initial
          <g>bh-</g>, i.e. <g>o</g>, <g>on</g>, <g>om</g>, <g>uam</g>, ...</p>
    </section>
    <section id="definite">
      <h>definite</h>
      <p>When the immediately following word is a singular form of the definite article, the linking
        form <g>bhon</g> is used – <ul>
          <li><m>bhon an</m> taigh <en>from the house</en></li>
          <li><m>bhon a’</m> bhaile <en>from the town</en></li>
        </ul> But – <ul>
          <li><m>bho na h-</m>aislingean <en>from the dreams</en>, rather than <bad>bhon na
              h-aislingean</bad></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Note that <g>bhon an</g> and <g>bhon a’</g> often occur as just <g>bhon</g> – <g>bhon
          taigh</g>, <g>bhon bhaile</g>.</p>
      <!--
      <p><g>bhon</g> is used in a range of other vowel-initial contexts as well – <ul>
          <li><g>bhon a-màireach</g>
            <en>from tomorrow</en></li>
          <li><g>bhon a h-uile ...</g>
            <en>from every ...</en></li>
          <li><g>bhon a bheil ...</g>
            <en>out of which ...</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      -->
      <p>Fused forms are sometimes found when the immediately following word is a <!--<a
          href="?xx=nouns/possessive_determiners">possessive determiner</a>-->
          possessive determiner – <ul>
          <li><m>bho mo</m> thaigh <en>from my house</en> ≈ <g>bhom</g> thaigh</li>
          <li><m>bho do</m> bhaile <en>from your town</en> ≈ <g>bhod</g> bhaile</li>
          <li><m>bho a h-</m>òran <en>from her song</en> ≈ <g>bho h-</g>òran</li>
          <li><m>bho a</m> chraoibh <en>from his tree</en> ≈ <g>bho</g> chraoibh</li>
          <li><m>bho ar n-</m>achadh <en>from our field</en> ≈ <g>bhar n-</g>achadh</li>
          <li><m>bho ur</m> leapannan <en>from your beds</en> ≈ <g>bhur</g> leapannan</li>
          <li><m>bho an</m> taighean <en>from their houses</en> ≈ <g>bhon</g> taighean</li>
          <li><m>bho am</m> baile <en>from their town</en> ≈ <g>bhom</g> baile</li>
        </ul></p>
      <p>Note that these fused forms are rather awkward and sometimes ambiguous and hence are best
        avoided in writing nowadays.</p>
    </section>
    <section id="pronouns">
      <h>prepositional pronouns</h>
      <p>Conjugated prepositions are used in place of <bad>bho mi</bad>, <bad>bho thu</bad>, ... ,
          <bad>bho iad</bad> – <ul>
          <li><m>bhuam</m>
            <en>from me</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuat</m>
            <en>from you</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuaipe</m>
            <en>from her/it</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuaithe</m>
            <en>from him/it</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuainn</m>
            <en>from us</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuaibh</m>
            <en>from you</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuapa</m>
            <en>from them</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>There are also emphatic forms (cf. <bad>bho mise</bad>, <bad>bho thusa</bad>, ... ,
          <bad>bho iadsan</bad>) – <ul>
          <li><m>bhuamsa</m>
            <en>from <emph>me</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>bhuatsa</m>
            <en>from <emph>you</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>bhuaipese</m>
            <en>from <emph>her/it</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>bhuaithe-san</m>
            <en>from <emph>him/it</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>bhuainne</m>
            <en>from <emph>us</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>bhuaibhse</m>
            <en>from <emph>you</emph></en></li>
          <li><m>bhuapasan</m>
            <en>from <emph>them</emph></en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Finally, there are also reflexive forms (cf. <bad>bho mi fhìn</bad>, <bad>bho thu
          fhèin</bad>, ... , <bad>bho iad fhèin</bad>) – <ul>
          <li><m>bhuam fhèin / fhìn</m>
            <en>from myself</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuat fhèin</m>
            <en>from yourself</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuaipe fhèin</m>
            <en>from herself/itself</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuaithe fhèin</m>
            <en>from himself/itself</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuainn fhèin / fhìn</m>
            <en>from ourselves</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuaibh fhèin</m>
            <en>from yourselves</en></li>
          <li><m>bhuapa fhèin</m>
            <en>from themselves</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h>dependents</h>
    <section id="deps-comps">
      <h>complements</h>
      <module status="bronze" id="bho_chionn">
        <h>bho chionn ...</h>
        <p><g>bho <!--<a href="?gd=ceann">chionn</a>-->chionn</g>
          <en>ago</en></p>
      </module>
    </section>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h>uses</h>
    <section id="uses-comp">
      <h>complement</h>
      <module status="bronze" id="rach_bho">
        <h>rach bho ...</h>
        <p><g><a href="?gd=rach">rach</a> bho ...</g>
          <en>go from somewhere</en>
        </p>
      </module>
      <module status="bronze" id="thig_bho">
        <h>thig bho ...</h>
        <p><g><a href="?gd=thig">thig</a> bho ...</g>
          <en>come from somewhere</en> – <ul>
            <li>Examples from Gairm – <xl id="thig_bho-gairm">
                <li>
                  <gd>Bha grunnan de ar luchd-leughaidh an dùil, nuair a nochd an àireamh mu
                    dheireadh de Ghairm, gu robh sin a’ strì ri buidheann shònraichte, no duine
                    sònraichte, a chur do ’n Phàrlamaid, agus bha wèireichean an telefon gu math
                    teth, uair no dhà, an déidh dhuinn <m>tighinn o ’n chlò</m>. Thog iad ceàrr
                    sinn.</gd>
                  <tr>Some of our readers were expecting [?], when the last issue of Gairm appeared,
                    that that was striving to send a particular group [party?], or a particular
                    person, to the Parliament, and the telephone wires were pretty hot,for an hour
                    or two [once or twice?], after we came from the printers. They misunderstood
                    us.</tr>
                  <ref text="400-49">td. 9, ‘Air an Spiris’</ref>
                </li>
              </xl></li>
          </ul>
        </p>

      </module>
    </section>
  </section>


</module>
